+{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_018pY81tipJ7vwxkicLtf5Ck","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→import { randomUUID } from 'node:crypto';\n     2→import type {\n     3→  Task,\n     4→  TaskOptions,\n     5→  TaskStatus,\n     6→  MiddlewareFn,\n     7→  ProcessorFn,\n     8→  ProgressCallback,\n     9→  Schedule,\n    10→  ScheduleOptions,\n    11→  ShutdownResult,\n    12→} from './types.js';\n    13→\n    14→const DEFAULT_QUEUE = 'default';\n    15→const DEFAULT_PRIORITY = 5;\n    16→const DEFAULT_MAX_RETRIES = 3;\n    17→const DEFAULT_BACKOFF_DELAY = 1000;\n    18→\n    19→export class TaskQueue {\n    20→  private tasks: Map<string, Task> = new Map();\n    21→  private queues: Map<string, Set<string>> = new Map();\n    22→  private deadLetterQueues: Map<string, Set<string>> = new Map();\n    23→  private concurrencyLimits: Map<string, number> = new Map();\n    24→  private middlewares: Map<string, MiddlewareFn[]> = new Map();\n    25→  private processors: Map<string, ProcessorFn> = new Map();\n    26→  private progressSubscriptions: Map<string, Set<ProgressCallback>> = new Map();\n    27→  private schedules: Map<string, Schedule> = new Map();\n    28→  private shutdownCallbacks: Array<() => void | Promise<void>> = [];\n    29→  private isShuttingDown = false;\n    30→  private shutdownPromise: Promise<ShutdownResult> | null = null;\n    31→  private sequenceCounter = 0;\n    32→  private taskSequence: Map<string, number> = new Map();\n    33→\n    34→  // ─── Phase 1: Basic Queue ───\n    35→\n    36→  addTask<T = unknown>(payload: T, options: TaskOptions = {}): Task<T> {\n    37→    if (this.isShuttingDown) {\n    38→      throw new Error('Cannot add tasks: system is shutting down');\n    39→    }\n    40→\n    41→    const queueName = options.queue ?? DEFAULT_QUEUE;\n    42→    const priority = options.priority ?? DEFAULT_PRIORITY;\n    43→\n    44→    if (priority < 1 || priority > 10 || !Number.isInteger(priority)) {\n    45→      throw new Error(`Invalid priority: ${priority}. Must be an integer between 1 and 10.`);\n    46→    }\n    47→\n    48→    const now = new Date();\n    49→    let availableAt = now;\n    50→\n    51→    if (options.availableAt) {\n    52→      availableAt = options.availableAt;\n    53→    } else if (options.delay != null && options.delay > 0) {\n    54→      availableAt = new Date(now.getTime() + options.delay);\n    55→    }\n    56→\n    57→    // Validate dependencies\n    58→    const dependencies = options.dependencies ?? [];\n    59→    for (const depId of dependencies) {\n    60→      if (!this.tasks.has(depId)) {\n    61→        throw new Error(`Dependency task not found: ${depId}`);\n    62→      }\n    63→    }\n    64→\n    65→    const taskId = randomUUID();\n    66→\n    67→    // Circular dependency detection\n    68→    if (dependencies.length > 0) {\n    69→      this.detectCircularDependencies(taskId, dependencies);\n    70→    }\n    71→\n    72→    const hasUnresolvedDeps = dependencies.some(depId => {\n    73→      const dep = this.tasks.get(depId)!;\n    74→      return dep.status !== 'completed';\n    75→    });\n    76→\n    77→    let status: TaskStatus = 'pending';\n    78→    if (hasUnresolvedDeps) {\n    79→      status = 'blocked';\n    80→    } else if (availableAt > now) {\n    81→      status = 'delayed';\n    82→    }\n    83→\n    84→    const task: Task<T> = {\n    85→      id: taskId,\n    86→      payload,\n    87→      status,\n    88→      priority,\n    89→      queue: queueName,\n    90→      createdAt: now,\n    91→      availableAt,\n    92→      attempt: 0,\n    93→      maxRetries: options.maxRetries ?? DEFAULT_MAX_RETRIES,\n    94→      backoffDelay: options.backoffDelay ?? DEFAULT_BACKOFF_DELAY,\n    95→      progress: 0,\n    96→      failureCount: 0,\n    97→      dependencies: [...dependencies],\n    98→      resolvedDependencies: new Set(\n    99→        dependencies.filter(depId => {\n   100→          const dep = this.tasks.get(depId)!;\n   101→          return dep.status === 'completed';\n   102→        })\n   103→      ),\n   104→    };\n   105→\n   106→    this.tasks.set(taskId, task as Task);\n   107→    this.ensureQueue(queueName);\n   108→    this.queues.get(queueName)!.add(taskId);\n   109→    this.taskSequence.set(taskId, this.sequenceCounter++);\n   110→\n   111→    return task;\n   112→  }\n   113→\n   114→  getTask<T = unknown>(taskId: string): Task<T> | null {\n   115→    return (this.tasks.get(taskId) as Task<T>) ?? null;\n   116→  }\n   117→\n   118→  // ─── Phase 2: Named Queues / Phase 1: Basic retrieval ───\n   119→\n   120→  getNextTask<T = unknown>(queueName: string = DEFAULT_QUEUE): Task<T> | null {\n   121→    const queue = this.queues.get(queueName);\n   122→    if (!queue) return null;\n   123→\n   124→    // Check concurrency limit\n   125→    const limit = this.concurrencyLimits.get(queueName);\n   126→    if (limit != null) {\n   127→      const activeCount = this.getActiveCount(queueName);\n   128→      if (activeCount >= limit) return null;\n   129→    }\n   130→\n   131→    const now = new Date();\n   132→\n   133→    // Collect eligible tasks: pending or delayed-but-now-available\n   134→    const eligible: Task[] = [];\n   135→    for (const taskId of queue) {\n   136→      const task = this.tasks.get(taskId)!;\n   137→      if (task.status === 'pending') {\n   138→        eligible.push(task);\n   139→      } else if (task.status === 'delayed' && task.availableAt <= now) {\n   140→        eligible.push(task);\n   141→      }\n   142→    }\n   143→\n   144→    if (eligible.length === 0) return null;\n   145→\n   146→    // Sort: priority (ascending, lower number = higher priority), then availability time, then FIFO (sequence)\n   147→    eligible.sort((a, b) => {\n   148→      if (a.priority !== b.priority) return a.priority - b.priority;\n   149→      const aTime = a.availableAt.getTime();\n   150→      const bTime = b.availableAt.getTime();\n   151→      if (aTime !== bTime) return aTime - bTime;\n   152→      return this.taskSequence.get(a.id)! - this.taskSequence.get(b.id)!;\n   153→    });\n   154→\n   155→    const task = eligible[0];\n   156→    task.status = 'processing';\n   157→    task.attempt += 1;\n   158→\n   159→    return task as Task<T>;\n   160→  }\n   161→\n   162→  getPendingCount(queueName: string = DEFAULT_QUEUE): number {\n   163→    const queue = this.queues.get(queueName);\n   164→    if (!queue) return 0;\n   165→\n   166→    let count = 0;\n   167→    const now = new Date();\n   168→    for (const taskId of queue) {\n   169→      const task = this.tasks.get(taskId)!;\n   170→      if (task.status === 'pending') {\n   171→        count++;\n   172→      } else if (task.status === 'delayed' && task.availableAt <= now) {\n   173→        count++;\n   174→      }\n   175→    }\n   176→    return count;\n   177→  }\n   178→\n   179→  getWaitingCount(queueName: string = DEFAULT_QUEUE): number {\n   180→    const queue = this.queues.get(queueName);\n   181→    if (!queue) return 0;\n   182→\n   183→    let count = 0;\n   184→    for (const taskId of queue) {\n   185→      const task = this.tasks.get(taskId)!;\n   186→      if (task.status === 'pending' || task.status === 'delayed' || task.status === 'blocked') {\n   187→        count++;\n   188→      }\n   189→    }\n   190→    return count;\n   191→  }\n   192→\n   193→  // ─── Phase 2: Named Queues ───\n   194→\n   195→  getQueues(): string[] {\n   196→    return Array.from(this.queues.keys());\n   197→  }\n   198→\n   199→  // ─── Phase 5: Complete / Fail ───\n   200→\n   201→  completeTask(taskId: string): void {\n   202→    const task = this.tasks.get(taskId);\n   203→    if (!task) throw new Error(`Task not found: ${taskId}`);\n   204→    if (task.status !== 'processing') {\n   205→      throw new Error(`Cannot complete task in '${task.status}' state`);\n   206→    }\n   207→\n   208→    task.status = 'completed';\n   209→    task.progress = 100;\n   210→\n   211→    // Check if any blocked tasks can now be unblocked\n   212→    this.checkDependents(taskId);\n   213→  }\n   214→\n   215→  failTask(taskId: string, error?: Error): void {\n   216→    const task = this.tasks.get(taskId);\n   217→    if (!task) throw new Error(`Task not found: ${taskId}`);\n   218→    if (task.status !== 'processing') {\n   219→      throw new Error(`Cannot fail task in '${task.status}' state`);\n   220→    }\n   221→\n   222→    task.error = error;\n   223→    task.failureCount += 1;\n   224→\n   225→    if (task.attempt < task.maxRetries) {\n   226→      // Retry with exponential backoff\n   227→      const delay = task.backoffDelay * Math.pow(2, task.attempt - 1);\n   228→      task.availableAt = new Date(Date.now() + delay);\n   229→      task.status = 'delayed';\n   230→      task.progress = 0;\n   231→    } else {\n   232→      // No retries left: move to dead letter queue\n   233→      task.status = 'dead-lettered';\n   234→      this.ensureDeadLetterQueue(task.queue);\n   235→      this.deadLetterQueues.get(task.queue)!.add(taskId);\n   236→      // Remove from main queue\n   237→      const queue = this.queues.get(task.queue);\n   238→      if (queue) queue.delete(taskId);\n   239→    }\n   240→  }\n   241→\n   242→  // ─── Phase 6: Dead Letter Queue ───\n   243→\n   244→  getDeadLetterTasks<T = unknown>(queueName: string = DEFAULT_QUEUE): Task<T>[] {\n   245→    const dlq = this.deadLetterQueues.get(queueName);\n   246→    if (!dlq) return [];\n   247→\n   248→    return Array.from(dlq).map(id => this.tasks.get(id) as Task<T>);\n   249→  }\n   250→\n   251→  redriveTask(taskId: string): Task {\n   252→    const task = this.tasks.get(taskId);\n   253→    if (!task) throw new Error(`Task not found: ${taskId}`);\n   254→    if (task.status !== 'dead-lettered') {\n   255→      throw new Error(`Task is not dead-lettered`);\n   256→    }\n   257→\n   258→    // Remove from DLQ\n   259→    const dlq = this.deadLetterQueues.get(task.queue);\n   260→    if (dlq) dlq.delete(taskId);\n   261→\n   262→    // Reset for fresh retries\n   263→    task.status = 'pending';\n   264→    task.attempt = 0;\n   265→    task.progress = 0;\n   266→    task.error = undefined;\n   267→    task.availableAt = new Date();\n   268→\n   269→    // Add back to main queue\n   270→    this.ensureQueue(task.queue);\n   271→    this.queues.get(task.queue)!.add(taskId);\n   272→\n   273→    return task;\n   274→  }\n   275→\n   276→  clearDeadLetterQueue(queueName: string = DEFAULT_QUEUE): number {\n   277→    const dlq = this.deadLetterQueues.get(queueName);\n   278→    if (!dlq) return 0;\n   279→\n   280→    const count = dlq.size;\n   281→    for (const taskId of dlq) {\n   282→      this.tasks.delete(taskId);\n   283→    }\n   284→    dlq.clear();\n   285→    return count;\n   286→  }\n   287→\n   288→  // ─── Phase 7: Task Dependencies ───\n   289→\n   290→  getTaskDependencyStatus(taskId: string): { total: number; resolved: number; pending: string[] } {\n   291→    const task = this.tasks.get(taskId);\n   292→    if (!task) throw new Error(`Task not found: ${taskId}`);\n   293→\n   294→    const pending = task.dependencies.filter(\n   295→      depId => !task.resolvedDependencies.has(depId)\n   296→    );\n   297→\n   298→    return {\n   299→      total: task.dependencies.length,\n   300→      resolved: task.resolvedDependencies.size,\n   301→      pending,\n   302→    };\n   303→  }\n   304→\n   305→  private detectCircularDependencies(newTaskId: string, dependencies: string[]): void {\n   306→    // Check if any dependency (transitively) would create a cycle\n   307→    // Since the new task doesn't exist yet, we check if any dependency\n   308→    // depends on something that would eventually depend on the new task.\n   309→    // But since the new task is new and no one depends on it yet,\n   310→    // we only need to check that dependencies don't form internal cycles.\n   311→    // Actually the real concern is: if task A depends on task B, and task B\n   312→    // depends on task A - but since newTaskId doesn't exist yet, no existing\n   313→    // task can depend on it. So circular deps can only occur if somehow\n   314→    // the dependencies themselves form a chain back to one of the dependencies.\n   315→    // For newly created tasks, we just need to ensure the dependency chain is valid.\n   316→    // Real cycles would be caught when someone tries to create a task that depends\n   317→    // on a task that (transitively) depends on an unresolved task that would need this one.\n   318→\n   319→    // Actually, since we're checking at creation time: a new task can't be part of a cycle\n   320→    // because no other task can reference it yet (it doesn't have an ID assigned yet in the graph).\n   321→    // However, we should check that the dependencies themselves don't contain cycles among themselves.\n   322→    // And we should check that we're not creating a situation where task A depends on B and B depends on A\n   323→    // indirectly.\n   324→\n   325→    // The real check: traverse dependencies of each dep - if any of them lead back to any dep, that's a cycle.\n   326→    // But since newTaskId is brand new and hasn't been added yet, no existing task can depend on it.\n   327→    // So there's no way to create a cycle with a brand new task. The existing tasks already had their\n   328→    // cycles checked when they were created.\n   329→\n   330→    // The only case for cycle detection at creation is: if the spec says \"depending on a task that\n   331→    // depends on this task\" - but this task doesn't exist yet. So cycle detection for new tasks is\n   332→    // essentially a no-op unless there are indirect chains among the deps themselves that were\n   333→    // somehow missed.\n   334→\n   335→    // To be safe, let's do BFS from each dependency - if we ever reach any of the other dependencies\n   336→    // through the dependency graph, flag it. Actually that's not a cycle, that's just a shared dependency.\n   337→\n   338→    // A cycle would be: if we find that any dependency transitively depends on a task that hasn't been\n   339→    // created yet. That can't happen. So the only check is verifying deps exist (done above).\n   340→\n   341→    // However, if we allow tasks to be added with deps on blocked tasks, and those blocked tasks\n   342→    // depend on other things that eventually might need this task - we need to check the full graph.\n   343→\n   344→    // Let's do the proper check: after conceptually adding newTaskId -> dependencies edges,\n   345→    // check if there's a cycle in the dependency graph.\n   346→\n   347→    // Build adjacency: task -> depends on\n   348→    const visited = new Set<string>();\n   349→    const stack = new Set<string>();\n   350→\n   351→    const hasCycle = (taskId: string): boolean => {\n   352→      if (stack.has(taskId)) return true;\n   353→      if (visited.has(taskId)) return false;\n   354→\n   355→      visited.add(taskId);\n   356→      stack.add(taskId);\n   357→\n   358→      const deps = taskId === newTaskId\n   359→        ? dependencies\n   360→        : (this.tasks.get(taskId)?.dependencies ?? []);\n   361→\n   362→      for (const dep of deps) {\n   363→        if (hasCycle(dep)) return true;\n   364→      }\n   365→\n   366→      stack.delete(taskId);\n   367→      return false;\n   368→    };\n   369→\n   370→    if (hasCycle(newTaskId)) {\n   371→      throw new Error('Circular dependency detected');\n   372→    }\n   373→  }\n   374→\n   375→  private checkDependents(completedTaskId: string): void {\n   376→    // Check all tasks to see if any are blocked on this task\n   377→    for (const [, task] of this.tasks) {\n   378→      if (task.status !== 'blocked') continue;\n   379→      if (!task.dependencies.includes(completedTaskId)) continue;\n   380→\n   381→      task.resolvedDependencies.add(completedTaskId);\n   382→\n   383→      // Check if all dependencies are now resolved\n   384→      const allResolved = task.dependencies.every(depId =>\n   385→        task.resolvedDependencies.has(depId)\n   386→      );\n   387→\n   388→      if (allResolved) {\n   389→        const now = new Date();\n   390→        if (task.availableAt > now) {\n   391→          task.status = 'delayed';\n   392→        } else {\n   393→          task.status = 'pending';\n   394→        }\n   395→      }\n   396→    }\n   397→  }\n   398→\n   399→  // ─── Phase 8: Concurrency Control ───\n   400→\n   401→  setConcurrency(queueName: string, limit: number): void {\n   402→    if (limit < 1 || !Number.isInteger(limit)) {\n   403→      throw new Error(`Invalid concurrency limit: ${limit}`);\n   404→    }\n   405→    this.concurrencyLimits.set(queueName, limit);\n   406→  }\n   407→\n   408→  getConcurrency(queueName: string): number | undefined {\n   409→    return this.concurrencyLimits.get(queueName);\n   410→  }\n   411→\n   412→  getActiveCount(queueName: string = DEFAULT_QUEUE): number {\n   413→    const queue = this.queues.get(queueName);\n   414→    if (!queue) return 0;\n   415→\n   416→    let count = 0;\n   417→    for (const taskId of queue) {\n   418→      const task = this.tasks.get(taskId)!;\n   419→      if (task.status === 'processing') count++;\n   420→    }\n   421→    return count;\n   422→  }\n   423→\n   424→  // ─── Phase 9: Progress Tracking and Cancellation ───\n   425→\n   426→  updateProgress(taskId: string, progress: number, message?: string): void {\n   427→    const task = this.tasks.get(taskId);\n   428→    if (!task) throw new Error(`Task not found: ${taskId}`);\n   429→    if (task.status !== 'processing') {\n   430→      throw new Error(`Cannot update progress for task in '${task.status}' state`);\n   431→    }\n   432→    if (progress < 0 || progress > 100) {\n   433→      throw new Error(`Invalid progress: ${progress}. Must be between 0 and 100.`);\n   434→    }\n   435→\n   436→    task.progress = progress;\n   437→    task.progressMessage = message;\n   438→\n   439→    // Notify subscribers\n   440→    const subs = this.progressSubscriptions.get(taskId);\n   441→    if (subs) {\n   442→      for (const callback of subs) {\n   443→        callback(progress, message);\n   444→      }\n   445→    }\n   446→  }\n   447→\n   448→  getProgress(taskId: string): { progress: number; message?: string } {\n   449→    const task = this.tasks.get(taskId);\n   450→    if (!task) throw new Error(`Task not found: ${taskId}`);\n   451→    return { progress: task.progress, message: task.progressMessage };\n   452→  }\n   453→\n   454→  onProgress(taskId: string, callback: ProgressCallback): () => void {\n   455→    if (!this.progressSubscriptions.has(taskId)) {\n   456→      this.progressSubscriptions.set(taskId, new Set());\n   457→    }\n   458→    this.progressSubscriptions.get(taskId)!.add(callback);\n   459→\n   460→    // Return unsubscribe function\n   461→    return () => {\n   462→      const subs = this.progressSubscriptions.get(taskId);\n   463→      if (subs) {\n   464→        subs.delete(callback);\n   465→        if (subs.size === 0) {\n   466→          this.progressSubscriptions.delete(taskId);\n   467→        }\n   468→      }\n   469→    };\n   470→  }\n   471→\n   472→  cancelTask(taskId: string): void {\n   473→    const task = this.tasks.get(taskId);\n   474→    if (!task) throw new Error(`Task not found: ${taskId}`);\n   475→\n   476→    if (task.status !== 'pending' && task.status !== 'processing' && task.status !== 'delayed' && task.status !== 'blocked') {\n   477→      throw new Error(`Cannot cancel task in '${task.status}' state`);\n   478→    }\n   479→\n   480→    const wasProcessing = task.status === 'processing';\n   481→    task.status = 'cancelled';\n   482→\n   483→    // Remove from queue if pending/delayed/blocked\n   484→    if (!wasProcessing) {\n   485→      const queue = this.queues.get(task.queue);\n   486→      if (queue) queue.delete(taskId);\n   487→    }\n   488→  }\n   489→\n   490→  // ─── Phase 10: Recurring Tasks ───\n   491→\n   492→  addSchedule(options: ScheduleOptions): Schedule {\n   493→    if (this.isShuttingDown) {\n   494→      throw new Error('Cannot add schedules: system is shutting down');\n   495→    }\n   496→\n   497→    const schedule: Schedule = {\n   498→      id: options.id,\n   499→      cron: options.cron,\n   500→      queue: options.queue,\n   501→      payload: options.payload,\n   502→      taskOptions: options.taskOptions,\n   503→    };\n   504→\n   505→    this.schedules.set(options.id, schedule);\n   506→    return schedule;\n   507→  }\n   508→\n   509→  removeSchedule(scheduleId: string): boolean {\n   510→    return this.schedules.delete(scheduleId);\n   511→  }\n   512→\n   513→  getSchedules(): Schedule[] {\n   514→    return Array.from(this.schedules.values());\n   515→  }\n   516→\n   517→  tick(now: Date = new Date()): Task[] {\n   518→    const createdTasks: Task[] = [];\n   519→\n   520→    for (const [, schedule] of this.schedules) {\n   521→      if (this.shouldRunSchedule(schedule, now)) {\n   522→        const task = this.addTask(schedule.payload, {\n   523→          queue: schedule.queue,\n   524→          ...schedule.taskOptions,\n   525→        });\n   526→        createdTasks.push(task);\n   527→        schedule.lastRun = now;\n   528→      }\n   529→    }\n   530→\n   531→    return createdTasks;\n   532→  }\n   533→\n   534→  private shouldRunSchedule(schedule: Schedule, now: Date): boolean {\n   535→    const { cron, lastRun } = schedule;\n   536→\n   537→    // Parse simple cron subset\n   538→    const parts = cron.split(/\\s+/);\n   539→    if (parts.length !== 5) return false;\n   540→\n   541→    const [minutePart, hourPart] = parts;\n   542→\n   543→    const currentMinute = now.getMinutes();\n   544→    const currentHour = now.getHours();\n   545→\n   546→    // Check minute match\n   547→    let minuteMatch = false;\n   548→    if (minutePart === '*') {\n   549→      minuteMatch = true;\n   550→    } else if (minutePart.startsWith('*/')) {\n   551→      const interval = parseInt(minutePart.slice(2), 10);\n   552→      minuteMatch = currentMinute % interval === 0;\n   553→    } else {\n   554→      minuteMatch = parseInt(minutePart, 10) === currentMinute;\n   555→    }\n   556→\n   557→    // Check hour match\n   558→    let hourMatch = false;\n   559→    if (hourPart === '*') {\n   560→      hourMatch = true;\n   561→    } else if (hourPart.startsWith('*/')) {\n   562→      const interval = parseInt(hourPart.slice(2), 10);\n   563→      hourMatch = currentHour % interval === 0;\n   564→    } else {\n   565→      hourMatch = parseInt(hourPart, 10) === currentHour;\n   566→    }\n   567→\n   568→    if (!minuteMatch || !hourMatch) return false;\n   569→\n   570→    // Prevent double-firing in the same minute\n   571→    if (lastRun) {\n   572→      const lastMinute = lastRun.getMinutes();\n   573→      const lastHour = lastRun.getHours();\n   574→      const lastDate = lastRun.toDateString();\n   575→      const nowDate = now.toDateString();\n   576→\n   577→      if (lastDate === nowDate && lastHour === currentHour && lastMinute === currentMinute) {\n   578→        return false;\n   579→      }\n   580→    }\n   581→\n   582→    return true;\n   583→  }\n   584→\n   585→  // ─── Phase 11: Middleware Pipeline ───\n   586→\n   587→  use(queueName: string, middleware: MiddlewareFn): void {\n   588→    if (!this.middlewares.has(queueName)) {\n   589→      this.middlewares.set(queueName, []);\n   590→    }\n   591→    this.middlewares.get(queueName)!.push(middleware);\n   592→  }\n   593→\n   594→  setProcessor<T = unknown>(queueName: string, processor: ProcessorFn<T>): void {\n   595→    this.processors.set(queueName, processor as ProcessorFn);\n   596→  }\n   597→\n   598→  async processNext(queueName: string = DEFAULT_QUEUE): Promise<Task | null> {\n   599→    const task = this.getNextTask(queueName);\n   600→    if (!task) return null;\n   601→\n   602→    const middlewareStack = this.middlewares.get(queueName) ?? [];\n   603→    const processor = this.processors.get(queueName);\n   604→\n   605→    try {\n   606→      let handlerReached = false;\n   607→\n   608→      const runPipeline = (index: number): Promise<void> => {\n   609→        if (index >= middlewareStack.length) {\n   610→          // End of middleware chain - run the processor\n   611→          handlerReached = true;\n   612→          if (processor && task.status === 'processing') {\n   613→            return processor(task);\n   614→          }\n   615→          return Promise.resolve();\n   616→        }\n   617→\n   618→        return middlewareStack[index](task, () => runPipeline(index + 1));\n   619→      };\n   620→\n   621→      await runPipeline(0);\n   622→\n   623→      if (!handlerReached) {\n   624→        // Middleware didn't call next - task processing was skipped\n   625→        if (task.status === 'processing') {\n   626→          task.status = 'pending';\n   627→          task.attempt -= 1;\n   628→        }\n   629→        return task;\n   630→      }\n   631→\n   632→      if (task.status === 'processing') {\n   633→        this.completeTask(task.id);\n   634→      }\n   635→    } catch (err) {\n   636→      if (task.status === 'processing') {\n   637→        this.failTask(task.id, err instanceof Error ? err : new Error(String(err)));\n   638→      }\n   639→    }\n   640→\n   641→    return task;\n   642→  }\n   643→\n   644→  // ─── Phase 12: Graceful Shutdown ───\n   645→\n   646→  onShutdown(callback: () => void | Promise<void>): void {\n   647→    this.shutdownCallbacks.push(callback);\n   648→  }\n   649→\n   650→  async shutdown(timeout: number = 30000): Promise<ShutdownResult> {\n   651→    if (this.shutdownPromise) {\n   652→      return this.shutdownPromise;\n   653→    }\n   654→\n   655→    this.isShuttingDown = true;\n   656→    this.shutdownPromise = this.performShutdown(timeout);\n   657→    return this.shutdownPromise;\n   658→  }\n   659→\n   660→  private async performShutdown(timeout: number): Promise<ShutdownResult> {\n   661→    const startTime = Date.now();\n   662→\n   663→    // Run shutdown callbacks\n   664→    for (const callback of this.shutdownCallbacks) {\n   665→      try {\n   666→        await callback();\n   667→      } catch {\n   668→        // Ignore callback errors during shutdown\n   669→      }\n   670→    }\n   671→\n   672→    // Find all currently processing tasks\n   673→    const processingTasks: Task[] = [];\n   674→    for (const [, task] of this.tasks) {\n   675→      if (task.status === 'processing') {\n   676→        processingTasks.push(task);\n   677→      }\n   678→    }\n   679→\n   680→    let completed = 0;\n   681→    let forceCancelled = 0;\n   682→\n   683→    if (processingTasks.length === 0) {\n   684→      return {\n   685→        completed: 0,\n   686→        forceCancelled: 0,\n   687→        elapsed: Date.now() - startTime,\n   688→      };\n   689→    }\n   690→\n   691→    // Wait for processing tasks to complete (with timeout)\n   692→    const waitPromise = new Promise<void>((resolve) => {\n   693→      const checkInterval = setInterval(() => {\n   694→        const stillProcessing = processingTasks.filter(t => t.status === 'processing');\n   695→        if (stillProcessing.length === 0) {\n   696→          clearInterval(checkInterval);\n   697→          resolve();\n   698→        }\n   699→      }, 10);\n   700→\n   701→      setTimeout(() => {\n   702→        clearInterval(checkInterval);\n   703→        resolve();\n   704→      }, timeout);\n   705→    });\n   706→\n   707→    await waitPromise;\n   708→\n   709→    // Count results\n   710→    for (const task of processingTasks) {\n   711→      if (task.status === 'completed') {\n   712→        completed++;\n   713→      } else if (task.status === 'processing') {\n   714→        // Force cancel\n   715→        task.status = 'cancelled';\n   716→        forceCancelled++;\n   717→      }\n   718→    }\n   719→\n   720→    return {\n   721→      completed,\n   722→      forceCancelled,\n   723→      elapsed: Date.now() - startTime,\n   724→    };\n   725→  }\n   726→\n   727→  get isShutdown(): boolean {\n   728→    return this.isShuttingDown;\n   729→  }\n   730→\n   731→  // ─── Helpers ───\n   732→\n   733→  private ensureQueue(queueName: string): void {\n   734→    if (!this.queues.has(queueName)) {\n   735→      this.queues.set(queueName, new Set());\n   736→    }\n   737→  }\n   738→\n   739→  private ensureDeadLetterQueue(queueName: string): void {\n   740→    if (!this.deadLetterQueues.has(queueName)) {\n   741→      this.deadLetterQueues.set(queueName, new Set());\n   742→    }\n   743→  }\n   744→}\n   745→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_019iahqrbC4FEUgDfhLF4Dn8","session_id":"d5a6ede0-da20-4658-b3ef-351c6e047148","uuid":"9258947e-2587-41e2-883f-568b5d723163"}
+{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_019iahqrbC4FEUgDfhLF4Dn8","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I'll analyze all the phases and the implementation to identify missing or incorrectly implemented requirements. Let me create a comprehensive comparison report.\n\n## Comprehensive Phase Requirements vs Implementation Analysis\n\nI've reviewed all 12 phase files and the complete implementation. Here's a detailed breakdown of requirements gaps and potential issues:\n\n### **PHASE 1: Basic FIFO Queue**\n\n**Requirement:** \"There should be a way to check how many tasks are waiting.\"\n- **Status:** POTENTIALLY MISSING/CONFLICTING\n- **Details:** Implementation has `getPendingCount()` which only counts `pending` and available `delayed` tasks, and `getWaitingCount()` which counts `pending`, `delayed`, AND `blocked` tasks. The phase doesn't mention \"blocked\" tasks (Phase 7), so there's ambiguity. The method name `getPendingCount` may be misleading if it should cover all waiting tasks.\n\n**Requirement:** \"Each task must have a unique identifier (e.g., UUID), a status, and a creation timestamp.\"\n- **Status:** IMPLEMENTED ✓\n\n**Requirement:** \"New tasks start in a 'pending' state.\"\n- **Status:** PARTIALLY IMPLEMENTED - Tasks can start as `pending`, `delayed`, or `blocked` depending on options. The base assumption is correct for basic Phase 1, but this interacts with later phases.\n\n---\n\n### **PHASE 2: Named Queues**\n\n**Requirement:** \"The API should remain backward-compatible with Phase 1 (omitting the queue name uses the default).\"\n- **Status:** IMPLEMENTED ✓\n- **Details:** `addTask()` and `getNextTask()` default to `DEFAULT_QUEUE`\n\n**Requirement:** \"Creating a queue happens implicitly when a task is first added to it.\"\n- **Status:** IMPLEMENTED ✓\n- **Details:** `ensureQueue()` is called in `addTask()`\n\nAll Phase 2 requirements appear properly implemented.\n\n---\n\n### **PHASE 3: Priority**\n\n**Requirement:** \"Invalid priority values (outside 1-10) should cause an error.\"\n- **Status:** IMPLEMENTED ✓\n- **Details:** Lines 44-46 validate priority\n\n**Requirement:** \"Tasks with the same priority are returned in FIFO order.\"\n- **Status:** IMPLEMENTED ✓\n- **Details:** Lines 146-153 sort by priority then availability time then sequence\n\nAll Phase 3 requirements appear properly implemented.\n\n---\n\n### **PHASE 4: Delayed and Scheduled Tasks**\n\n**Requirement:** \"When multiple delayed tasks become available simultaneously, they should be ordered by availability time, then priority, then FIFO.\"\n- **Status:** IMPLEMENTED ✓\n- **Details:** Lines 146-153 correctly implement this ordering\n\n**Requirement:** \"Non-delayed tasks are always preferred over delayed tasks that are not yet available.\"\n- **Status:** IMPLEMENTED ✓\n- **Details:** Eligible collection on lines 133-142 only includes delayed tasks that are available now\n\nAll Phase 4 requirements appear properly implemented.\n\n---\n\n### **PHASE 5: Retry with Backoff**\n\n**Requirement:** \"The delay follows exponential backoff: `baseDelay * 2^(attempt - 1)` (e.g., 1s, 2s, 4s, ...).\"\n- **Status:** IMPLEMENTED ✓\n- **Details:** Line 227 correctly calculates this\n\n**Requirement:** \"Retried tasks keep their original queue and priority.\"\n- **Status:** IMPLEMENTED ✓\n- **Details:** Lines 228-229 maintain queue and priority\n\n**Requirement:** \"The default maximum number of retries is 3, but this should be configurable per task.\"\n- **Status:** IMPLEMENTED ✓\n- **Details:** Line 93 uses `options.maxRetries ?? DEFAULT_MAX_RETRIES`\n\n**Requirement:** \"The base backoff delay defaults to 1000ms but should be configurable per task.\"\n- **Status:** IMPLEMENTED ✓\n- **Details:** Line 94 uses `options.backoffDelay ?? DEFAULT_BACKOFF_DELAY`\n\nAll Phase 5 requirements appear properly implemented.\n\n---\n\n### **PHASE 6: Dead Letter Queue**\n\n**Requirement:** \"Dead-lettered tasks should retain their error information and a count of how many times they failed.\"\n- **Status:** IMPLEMENTED ✓\n- **Details:** Lines 222-223 set `task.error` and increment `task.failureCount`\n\n**Requirement:** \"There should be a way to view all dead-lettered tasks for a given queue.\"\n- **Status:** IMPLEMENTED ✓\n- **Details:** `getDeadLetterTasks()` method exists\n\n**Requirement:** \"It should be possible to move a dead-lettered task back to its original queue for a fresh round of retries.\"\n- **Status:** IMPLEMENTED ✓\n- **Details:** `redriveTask()` method exists\n\n**Requirement:** \"There should be a way to clear all dead-lettered tasks for a queue.\"\n- **Status:** IMPLEMENTED ✓\n- **Details:** `clearDeadLetterQueue()` method exists\n\nAll Phase 6 requirements appear properly implemented.\n\n---\n\n### **PHASE 7: Task Dependencies**\n\n**Requirement:** \"Depending on a non-existent task should cause an error.\"\n- **Status:** IMPLEMENTED ✓\n- **Details:** Lines 59-63 validate dependencies exist\n\n**Requirement:** \"Circular dependencies (direct or indirect) must be detected and rejected at task-creation time.\"\n- **Status:** IMPLEMENTED ✓\n- **Details:** Lines 68-70 call `detectCircularDependencies()` with proper cycle detection (lines 305-373)\n\n**Requirement:** \"A failed dependency does NOT automatically fail its dependents -- they remain blocked.\"\n- **Status:** IMPLEMENTED ✓\n- **Details:** `failTask()` doesn't unblock dependents; only `completeTask()` calls `checkDependents()`\n\n**Requirement:** \"When a dependency completes, the system should check whether any blocked tasks are now unblocked.\"\n- **Status:** IMPLEMENTED ✓\n- **Details:** Lines 211-212 call `checkDependents()` in `completeTask()`\n\n**Requirement:** \"There should be a way to inspect a task's dependency status.\"\n- **Status:** IMPLEMENTED ✓\n- **Details:** `getTaskDependencyStatus()` method exists\n\n**Requirement:** \"A task with unresolved dependencies is blocked and will not be returned when retrieving.\"\n- **Status:** IMPLEMENTED ✓\n- **Details:** Lines 133-142 only collect `pending` or available `delayed` tasks; blocked tasks are never eligible\n\nAll Phase 7 requirements appear properly implemented.\n\n---\n\n### **PHASE 8: Concurrency Control**\n\n**Requirement:** \"If the concurrency limit is reached, retrieving a task returns `null` even if pending tasks are available.\"\n- **Status:** IMPLEMENTED ✓\n- **Details:** Lines 124-129 check concurrency before returning\n\n**Requirement:** \"By default, queues have no concurrency limit (unlimited).\"\n- **Status:** IMPLEMENTED ✓\n- **Details:** `concurrencyLimits` is initially empty; check uses `?? null`\n\n**Requirement:** \"Concurrency interacts correctly with priority ordering -- the highest-priority available task is still chosen, subject to the concurrency limit.\"\n- **Status:** IMPLEMENTED ✓\n- **Details:** Concurrency check happens before sorting, so priority is preserved when a task is available\n\n**Requirement:** \"There should be a way to set and query the concurrency limit and current active count for a queue.\"\n- **Status:** IMPLEMENTED ✓\n- **Details:** `setConcurrency()`, `getConcurrency()`, and `getActiveCount()` methods exist\n\nAll Phase 8 requirements appear properly implemented.\n\n---\n\n### **PHASE 9: Progress Tracking and Cancellation**\n\n**Requirement:** \"A processing task can report its progress as a percentage (0-100) with an optional message.\"\n- **Status:** IMPLEMENTED ✓\n- **Details:** `updateProgress()` exists (lines 426-446)\n\n**Requirement:** \"There should be a way to query a task's current progress.\"\n- **Status:** IMPLEMENTED ✓\n- **Details:** `getProgress()` method exists\n\n**Requirement:** \"Listeners can subscribe to progress updates for a task and receive notifications when progress changes.\"\n- **Status:** IMPLEMENTED ✓\n- **Details:** `onProgress()` method exists and calls callbacks (lines 440-445)\n\n**Requirement:** \"Subscriptions should be cancellable (unsubscribe).\"\n- **Status:** IMPLEMENTED ✓\n- **Details:** `onProgress()` returns unsubscribe function\n\n**Requirement:** \"Tasks in pending or processing state can be cancelled.\"\n- **Status:** PARTIALLY IMPLEMENTED\n- **Issue:** Line 476 allows cancelling `pending`, `processing`, `delayed`, AND `blocked` tasks. The requirement specifies only `pending` or `processing`. Phase 9 doesn't mention delayed or blocked tasks being cancellable.\n\n**Requirement:** \"Cancelled pending tasks are removed from the queue and will not be returned.\"\n- **Status:** IMPLEMENTED ✓\n- **Details:** Lines 484-487 remove from queue if not processing\n\n**Requirement:** \"Cancelled processing tasks have their status updated accordingly.\"\n- **Status:** IMPLEMENTED ✓\n- **Details:** Line 481 sets status to `cancelled`\n\n**Requirement:** \"Cancelled tasks are never retried, even if they had retries remaining.\"\n- **Status:** IMPLEMENTED ✓\n- **Details:** `cancelled` is not a retryable state; `failTask()` only processes `processing` tasks\n\n**Issue Found:** Line 476 allows cancelling `delayed` and `blocked` tasks, but Phase 9 only specifies `pending` or `processing`.\n\n---\n\n### **PHASE 10: Recurring Tasks**\n\n**Requirement:** \"Support a simple subset of cron expressions: `*/N * * * *` -- every N minutes; `0 * * * *` -- every hour on the hour; `0 0 * * *` -- every day at midnight.\"\n- **Status:** PARTIALLY IMPLEMENTED\n- **Issue:** The `shouldRunSchedule()` function (lines 534-583) has a bug in minute parsing:\n  - Line 552: `currentMinute % interval === 0` is incorrect for `*/N` cron expressions\n  - For example, `*/5` (every 5 minutes) would run at minutes 0, 5, 10, 15, etc., but `15 % 5 === 0` is true, so it would run correctly. However, `3 % 5 !== 0`, so minute 3 wouldn't match `*/5`. **This is actually correct.**\n  - Wait, let me reconsider: `*/5` means \"every 5 minutes starting from minute 0\", so minutes 0, 5, 10, 15, 20, 25, 30, 35, 40, 45, 50, 55. The modulo check `currentMinute % interval === 0` correctly identifies these.\n  - **Actually, this appears correct.** ✓\n\n**Requirement:** \"A schedule associates a cron expression with a queue and a task template (the payload to use each time).\"\n- **Status:** IMPLEMENTED ✓\n- **Details:** Lines 492-507\n\n**Requirement:** \"There should be a way to create, remove, and list active schedules.\"\n- **Status:** IMPLEMENTED ✓\n- **Details:** `addSchedule()`, `removeSchedule()`, `getSchedules()` methods exist\n\n**Requirement:** \"A manual 'tick' or 'check' mechanism should evaluate all active schedules and enqueue tasks for any that are due.\"\n- **Status:** IMPLEMENTED ✓\n- **Details:** `tick()` method exists\n\n**Requirement:** \"Removing a schedule stops future occurrences from being created.\"\n- **Status:** IMPLEMENTED ✓\n- **Details:** `removeSchedule()` deletes from `schedules` map\n\n**CRITICAL ISSUE:** Lines 541-554 only parse the first two parts of the cron expression (minute and hour). The requirement specifies three different cron formats:\n- `*/N * * * *` - parsed correctly\n- `0 * * * *` - parsed correctly  \n- `0 0 * * *` - **NOT parsed correctly** - requires checking day-of-month, which isn't implemented\n\nThe function returns `false` if `parts.length !== 5` (line 539), but the logic only checks minute and hour. For the `0 0 * * *` pattern (every day at midnight), the day field (parts[2]) is ignored.\n\n---\n\n### **PHASE 11: Middleware Pipeline**\n\n**Requirement:** \"Middleware functions can be registered per queue.\"\n- **Status:** IMPLEMENTED ✓\n- **Details:** `use()` method exists\n\n**Requirement:** \"When a task is processed, it passes through all registered middleware in order before reaching the final handler.\"\n- **Status:** IMPLEMENTED ✓\n- **Details:** `runPipeline()` function (lines 608-619) chains middleware\n\n**Requirement:** \"Each middleware receives the task and a 'next' function. Calling 'next' passes control to the next middleware (or the handler).\"\n- **Status:** IMPLEMENTED ✓\n- **Details:** Line 618 passes task and next function\n\n**Requirement:** \"If a middleware does NOT call 'next', the task processing is skipped.\"\n- **Status:** IMPLEMENTED ✓\n- **Details:** Lines 623-629 handle this case\n\n**Requirement:** \"Middleware can modify the task (e.g., adding metadata or transforming the payload).\"\n- **Status:** IMPLEMENTED ✓\n- **Details:** Task is passed by reference and can be modified\n\n**Requirement:** \"If a middleware throws an error, the task should be marked as failed.\"\n- **Status:** IMPLEMENTED ✓\n- **Details:** Lines 635-638 catch errors and call `failTask()`\n\n**Requirement:** \"A processing function/handler can be registered per queue. It is invoked after all middleware have run.\"\n- **Status:** IMPLEMENTED ✓\n- **Details:** `setProcessor()` method exists; processor is called at line 613\n\n**Requirement:** \"Each queue has its own independent middleware stack.\"\n- **Status:** IMPLEMENTED ✓\n- **Details:** Middleware stored per queue in `Map<string, MiddlewareFn[]>`\n\nAll Phase 11 requirements appear properly implemented.\n\n---\n\n### **PHASE 12: Graceful Shutdown**\n\n**Requirement:** \"A shutdown operation should signal the system to stop accepting new tasks.\"\n- **Status:** IMPLEMENTED ✓\n- **Details:** `isShuttingDown` flag is checked in `addTask()` (line 37) and `addSchedule()` (line 493)\n\n**Requirement:** \"After shutdown is initiated, attempting to add new tasks should produce an error.\"\n- **Status:** IMPLEMENTED ✓\n- **Details:** Lines 37-39 throw error\n\n**Requirement:** \"The shutdown should wait for all currently-processing tasks to finish, up to a configurable timeout.\"\n- **Status:** IMPLEMENTED ✓\n- **Details:** Lines 691-707 implement wait with timeout\n\n**Requirement:** \"If processing tasks do not complete within the timeout, they should be force-cancelled.\"\n- **Status:** IMPLEMENTED ✓\n- **Details:** Lines 713-717 force-cancel remaining processing tasks\n\n**Requirement:** \"Callbacks can be registered to run during the shutdown process.\"\n- **Status:** IMPLEMENTED ✓\n- **Details:** `onShutdown()` method exists\n\n**Requirement:** \"The shutdown should produce a summary indicating how many tasks completed, how many were force-cancelled, and how long the shutdown took.\"\n- **Status:** IMPLEMENTED ✓\n- **Details:** Lines 720-724 return `ShutdownResult`\n\n**Requirement:** \"Calling shutdown multiple times should be safe and return the same result.\"\n- **Status:** IMPLEMENTED ✓\n- **Details:** Lines 651-657 return cached `shutdownPromise`\n\n**Requirement:** \"If no tasks are processing, shutdown should complete immediately.\"\n- **Status:** IMPLEMENTED ✓\n- **Details:** Lines 683-689 return immediately if no processing tasks\n\nAll Phase 12 requirements appear properly implemented.\n\n---\n\n## Summary of Issues Found\n\n### Critical Issues:\n1. **Phase 10 - Cron Expression Parsing:** The `shouldRunSchedule()` function only parses minute and hour fields. The `0 0 * * *` pattern (every day at midnight) cannot be correctly identified because the day-of-month field is never checked. **This will cause daily scheduled tasks to fire every hour (when both minute and hour are 0) rather than once per day.**\n\n### Medium Issues:\n2. **Phase 9 - Cancellation Scope:** The `cancelTask()` method allows cancelling `delayed` and `blocked` tasks, but Phase 9 requirements only specify `pending` or `processing` states should be cancellable. This might be intentional cross-phase design, but it's not documented in Phase 9.\n\n### Minor Issues:\n3. **Phase 1 - Ambiguous \"Waiting\" Definition:** The phase mentions \"check how many tasks are waiting\" but the implementation provides both `getPendingCount()` and `getWaitingCount()`. The API is ambiguous about which one fulfills the requirement, and `getWaitingCount()` includes `blocked` tasks which weren't mentioned in Phase 1.\n\nAll other requirements from Phases 1-